{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626361"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:36:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:36:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17069"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17069"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.28,0.3,0.33,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77398"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9759"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62905"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5279"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23167"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77398"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (NRTIs) are a key component of antiretroviral therapy for Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) infection. These medications must undergo intracellular modification before becoming active.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prevents assembly of viral RNA into capsid proteins","Blocks integration of viral DNA into host genome","Terminates viral DNA chain elongation","Prevents viral attachment to CD4 receptors","Blocks processing of viral polyprotein precursors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eterminating viral DNA chain elongation\u003C/strong\u003E. These drugs are phosphorylated inside cells to their active form, which then competes with natural nucleosides. When incorporated into the growing viral DNA chain, they prevent further elongation, thereby stopping viral replication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents assembly of viral RNA into capsid proteins\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism of NRTIs, which act specifically on reverse transcription.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks integration of viral DNA into host genome\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of integrase inhibitors such as raltegravir.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents viral attachment to CD4 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of entry inhibitors such as maraviroc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks processing of viral polyprotein precursors\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of protease inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENRTIs are considered prodrugs because they require phosphorylation by cellular kinases to become active. Once activated, they specifically target the reverse transcriptase enzyme unique to retroviruses like HIV.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors are prodrugs. They require intracellular phosphorylation to become active.","Active nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors compete with natural nucleosides and terminate viral DNA chain elongation.","Nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors specifically target HIV reverse transcriptase enzyme to prevent viral replication."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62905"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17069"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62905"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T21:39:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T21:39:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9759"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77398"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co